Our Accumulated Abstract Knowledge tolds us the proven geometrical axioms, such as "Orthocenter, Circumcenter, Gravity Point creates one line."
However, in order for us to understand the axiom above, we should always interpret the abstract knowledge into the geometrical shapes.
The Euclidian lines and circles above offers us a bridge linking to the abstract world, but still it takes part within the descriptive images.
My purpose of this project was to test the possibility of these Euclidian images, and highlight its descriptiveness rather than abstractness.
I questioned the following: Can Euclidian lines and circles themselves can create an aesthetic impression?

Each of the circle represents the specific time of the day.

The first row
The beginning of the day.
6:37 The Rise, A circle situated between two lines express the rise of the sun.
9:14 The Power, Powerful perpendicular line breaking through the semicircle.
10:58 The Euphorion, Inspired from Goethe's Faust
12:07 Harmony of Daytime, Circle and surrounding lines blended harmonically

The second row
"What goes up must goes down"
14:12 Disputation, Surrounded by confusing Geometrical lines and circles
16:26 Pressure and Agony, Outer circles represent pressure, inner lines represent agony
18:47 Apocalypse, Sun setting down with its own agony
19:08 The sign of Absencse, A magical hour coming just after the sunset

The last row
Series of pure abstract shapes.
21:33 Stability of Nighttime, perpendicular lines and tangent circles giving balanced impression
23:47 Lunar Dream I, A geometrical fantasy
2:03 Lunar Dream II, shape on its transition to the circle
5:23 Rebirth, Circle leaves the rectangle, preparing its rebirth
